## What you will learn in this notebook:
1. Load a CSV file from our Github Repo [Python]
2. Ingest that file into a SingleStoreDB without defining the schema [Python]
3. Interact natively with the database using SQL [SQL]
4. Visualize results with Plotly [Python]
## Enhance your notebook with visualization
## 0. Import the libraries for that guide for using dataframes and visualizing date

!pip3 install emoji --upgrade
import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px
import emoji
## 1. Load a csv file hosted in Github using Python

url = 'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/singlestore-labs/singlestoredb-samples/main/Sample%20datasets/csv/Restaurant_Scores_LIVES_Standard.csv'
df = pd.read_csv(url,index_col=0,parse_dates=[0])
display(df)
## 2. Ingest a dataframe in a SingleStoreDB table

1. Create the database
2. Import the library to connect to the database
3. Create the connection to the library
4. Ingest the dataframe to the newly created database

%%sql
CREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS getting_started_notebook;
from sqlalchemy import create_engine

database_name = 'getting_started_notebook'
db_connection_str = "mysql+pymysql://"+connection_user+":"+connection_password+"@"+connection_host+":"+connection_port+"/"+database_name+"?ssl_cipher=HIGH"
db_connection = create_engine(db_connection_str)

df.to_sql('sf_restaurant_scores', con = db_connection, if_exists = 'append', 
index = False, chunksize = 1000)
## 3. Interact natively with the database using SQL

1. Read the top 10 rows from the table
2. Alter the table to get the date in a date format, not string
3. Read the number of restaurant inspections over the time in San Francisco

%%sql
SELECT
    *
FROM
    getting_started_notebook.sf_restaurant_scores
LIMIT
    10;

%%sql result1 <<
USE getting_started_notebook;
SELECT
    DATE_TRUNC('month', inspection_date_new) AS month,
    COUNT(*) AS count_inspection
FROM
    getting_started_notebook.sf_restaurant_scores
GROUP BY
    MONTH
ORDER BY
    MONTH DESC;
## 4. Visualize with Plotly

df = pd.DataFrame(result1)

fig = px.bar(df, x = "month", y = "count_inspection",
              title = "Inspections by Month")

fig.show()
## 5. Cleanup Getting Started

%%sql
drop database getting_started_notebook;
